00:15.680 --> 00:18.380
THE PICTURE OF DORIAN GREY

00:19.140 --> 00:20.200
By Oscar Wilde

00:21.320 --> 00:23.060
As read by John Gonzales

00:23.680 --> 00:26.320
www.jongon.com

00:27.740 --> 00:29.000
CHAPTER TWO

00:30.220 --> 00:37.960
As they entered they saw Dorian Gray. He was seated at the piano with his back to them,

00:37.960 --> 00:42.460
turning over the pages of a volume of Schumann's Forest Scenes.

00:43.900 --> 00:49.080
"'You must lend me these, Basil,' he cried. I want to learn them. They are perfectly

00:49.980 --> 00:50.540
charming."

00:50.540 --> 00:54.040
"'That entirely depends on how you sit to-day, Dorian.'

00:54.040 --> 00:55.960
"'Oh, I'm tired of sitting.'

00:56.920 --> 01:01.120
"'And I don't want a life-size portrait of myself,' answered the lad, swinging around

01:01.120 --> 01:06.760
on the music-stool in a willful, petulant manner. When he got sight of Lord Henry, a

01:06.760 --> 01:12.440
faint blush coloured his cheeks for a moment, and he started up. I beg your pardon, Basil,

01:12.960 --> 01:20.260
but I didn't know you had any one with you. This is Lord Henry Wooten, Dorian, an old Oxford

01:20.260 --> 01:25.160
friend of mine. I've just been telling him what a capital sitter you were, and now you've

01:25.160 --> 01:25.880
spoiled everything.'

01:27.520 --> 01:33.220
"'You have not spoiled my pleasure in meeting you, Mr. Gray,' said Lord Henry, stepping

01:33.220 --> 01:38.560
forward and shaking him by the hand. My aunt has often spoken to me about you. You are

01:38.560 --> 01:43.940
one of her favourites, and, I am afraid, one of her victims, too.'

01:44.540 --> 01:50.020
"'I am in Lady Agatha's black books at present,' answered Dorian, with a funny look of penance.

01:51.360 --> 01:56.740
"'I promised to go to her club in Whitechapel with her last Tuesday, and I really forgot

01:56.740 --> 02:02.320
all about it. We were to have played a duet together—three duets, I believe. I don't

02:02.320 --> 02:07.440
know what she will say to me. I'm far too frightened a call.'

02:08.300 --> 02:13.720
"'Oh, I will make your peace with my aunt. She is quite devoted to you, and I don't think

02:13.720 --> 02:18.500
it really matters about your not being there. The audience probably thought it was a duet.

02:18.720 --> 02:24.860
When Aunt Agatha sits down to the piano, she makes quite enough noise for two people.'

02:25.820 --> 02:32.160
"'That is very horrid to her, and not very nice to me,' answered Dorian, laughing. Lord

02:32.160 --> 02:38.300
Henry looked at him. Yes, he was certainly wonderfully handsome, with his finely curved

02:38.300 --> 02:44.360
scarlet lips, his frank blue eyes, his crisp gold hair. There was something in his face

02:44.360 --> 02:51.560
that made one trust him at once. All the candour of youth was there, as well as all youth's

02:51.560 --> 02:58.840
passionate purity. One felt that he had kept himself unspotted from the world. No wonder

02:58.840 --> 03:04.080
Basil Hallward worshipped him. He was made to be worshipped.'

03:05.420 --> 03:12.440
"'You're too charming to go into philanthropy, Mr. Grey—far too charming.' And Lord Henry

03:12.440 --> 03:18.860
flung himself down on the divan and opened his cigarette-case. Hallward had been busy

03:18.860 --> 03:27.020
mixing his colours and getting his brushes ready. He was looking worried, and when he

03:27.020 --> 03:30.060
glanced at him hesitated for a moment, and then said,

03:31.220 --> 03:37.220
"'Hurry, I want to finish this picture to-day. Would you think it awfully rude of me if I

03:37.220 --> 03:43.920
asked you to go away?' Lord Henry smiled and looked at Dorian Grey.

03:44.920 --> 03:48.900
"'Am I to go, Mr. Grey?' he asked.

03:49.320 --> 03:54.780
"'Oh, please don't, Lord Henry. I see that Basil is in one of his sulky moods, and I

03:54.780 --> 04:01.980
dare him when he sulks. Besides, I want you to tell me why I should not go in for philanthropy.'

04:02.640 --> 04:08.600
"'I don't know that I shall tell you that, Mr. Grey, but I certainly will not run away,

04:08.900 --> 04:15.020
now that you have asked me to stop. You don't really mind, do you, Basil? You've often told

04:15.020 --> 04:21.940
me that you liked your sitters to have someone to chat to.'

04:21.940 --> 04:23.000
Lord Henry would bit his lip.

04:23.980 --> 04:30.740
"'If Dorian wishes it, of course you must stay.' Dorian's whims are laws to everybody,

04:31.620 --> 04:32.620
except himself.

04:33.720 --> 04:36.040
Lord Henry took up his hat and gloves.

04:37.240 --> 04:43.700
"'You are very pressing, Basil, but I am afraid I must go. I have promised to meet a man at

04:43.700 --> 04:50.420
the Orléans. Good-bye, Mr. Grey. Come and see me some afternoon in Curzon Street. I

04:50.420 --> 04:54.100
am nearly always at home at five o'clock. Write to me when you are coming. I should

04:54.100 --> 04:56.420
be sorry to miss you.'

04:57.360 --> 05:03.300
"'Basil,' cried Dorian Grey, "'if Lord Henry goes, I shall go, too. You never open your

05:03.300 --> 05:07.020
lips when you are painting, and it is horribly dull standing on a platform and trying to

05:07.020 --> 05:13.940
look pleasant. Ask him to stay. I insist upon it. Stay, Harry, to oblige Dorian.'

05:14.460 --> 05:20.460
"'And to oblige me,' said Hallward, gazing intently at his picture.

05:21.220 --> 05:26.020
"'It is quite true. I never talk when I am working, and never listen either, and it must

05:26.020 --> 05:31.400
be dreadfully tedious for my unfortunate sitters. I beg you to stay.'

05:31.400 --> 05:35.780
"'But what about my man at the Orléans?' Hallward laughed.

05:36.900 --> 05:43.020
"'I don't think that there will be any difficulty about that. Sit down again, Harry. And now,

05:43.940 --> 05:47.860
get up on that platform, and don't move about too much, or pay any attention to what Lord

05:47.860 --> 05:54.740
Henry says. He is a very bad influence over all his friends, with the exception of myself.'

05:56.100 --> 06:01.920
Dorian stepped up on the dais with the air of a young Greek martyr, and made a little

06:01.920 --> 06:08.700
moo-ay of discontent to Lord Henry, to whom he had rather taken a fancy. He was so unlike

06:08.700 --> 06:14.840
Hallward. They made a delightful contrast, and he had such a beautiful voice. After

06:14.840 --> 06:16.420
a few moments he said to him,

06:17.760 --> 06:23.440
"'Have you really a bad influence, Lord Henry, as bad as Basil says?'

06:24.200 --> 06:32.120
"'There's no such thing as a good influence, Mr. Grey. All influence is immoral. Immoral

06:32.120 --> 06:35.360
from the scientific point of view.'

06:35.360 --> 06:42.740
"'Why? Because to influence a person is to give him one's own soul. He does not think

06:42.740 --> 06:49.020
his natural thoughts, or burn with his natural passions. His virtues are not real to him.

06:49.060 --> 06:56.200
His sins, if there are such things as sins, are borrowed. He becomes an echo of someone

06:56.200 --> 07:01.580
else's music, an actor of a part that has not been written for him. The aim of life

07:01.580 --> 07:08.020
is self-development. To realize one's nature perfectly, that is what each of us is here

07:08.020 --> 07:16.360
for. People are afraid of themselves nowadays. They have forgotten the highest of all duties,

07:16.440 --> 07:23.860
the duty that one owes to oneself. Of course they are charitable, they feed the hungry

07:23.860 --> 07:31.140
and clothe the beggar, but their own souls starve and are naked. Courage has gone out

07:31.140 --> 07:36.560
of our race. Perhaps we never really had it. The terror of society, which is the basis

07:36.560 --> 07:41.980
of morals, the terror of God, which is the secret of religion, these are the two things

07:41.980 --> 07:47.320
that govern us. And yet, just turn your head a little to the right, Dorian, like a good

07:47.320 --> 07:52.740
boy,' said Hallward, deep in his work, and conscious only that a look had come into the

07:52.740 --> 07:55.100
lad's face that he had never seen there before.

07:56.220 --> 08:03.780
"'And yet,' continued Lord Henry, in his low musical voice, and with that graceful wave

08:03.780 --> 08:09.680
of the hand that was always so characteristic of him and that he had even in his Eden days,

08:10.480 --> 08:16.580
I believe that if one man were to live his life out fully and completely, were to give

08:16.580 --> 08:22.560
form to every feeling, expression to every thought, reality to every dream, I believe

08:22.560 --> 08:28.280
that the world would gain such a fresh impulse of joy that we would forget all the maladies

08:28.280 --> 08:35.540
of medievalism and return to the Hellenic ideal, to something finer, richer than the

08:35.540 --> 08:44.640
Hellenic ideal it may be. But the bravest man among us is afraid of himself. The mutilation

08:44.640 --> 08:51.620
of the savage has its tragic survival in the self-denial that marrs our lives. We are punished

08:51.620 --> 08:59.360
for our refusals. Every impulse that we strive to strangle broods in the mind and poisons

08:59.360 --> 09:05.220
us. The body sins once and has done with the sin, for action is a mode of purification.

09:05.340 --> 09:13.220
Nothing remains then but the recollection of a pleasure or the luxury of a regret. The

09:13.220 --> 09:20.360
only way to get rid of a temptation is to yield to it, resist it, and your soul grows

09:20.360 --> 09:27.760
sick with longing for the things it has forbidden to itself, with desire for what its monstrous

09:27.760 --> 09:36.060
laws have made monstrous and unlawful. It has been said that the great events of the

09:36.060 --> 09:43.000
world take place in the brain. It is in the brain and the brain only that the great sins

09:43.000 --> 09:49.360
of the world take place also. You, Mr. Grey, you yourself, with your rose-red youth and

09:49.360 --> 09:55.700
rose-white boyhood, you have had passions that have made you afraid, thoughts that have

09:55.700 --> 10:03.940
filled you with terror, day-dreams and sleeping-dreams whose mere memory might stain your cheek with

10:03.940 --> 10:11.300
shame. Stop, Murmuring Grace, stop, you bewilder me. I don't know what to say. There is some

10:11.300 --> 10:17.100
answer to you, but I cannot find it. Don't speak. Let me think, or rather let me try

10:17.100 --> 10:25.660
not to think. For nearly ten minutes he stood there motionless, with parted lips and eyes

10:25.660 --> 10:32.620
strangely bright. He was dimly conscious that entirely fresh impulses were at work within

10:32.620 --> 10:40.940
him, and they seemed to him to have come really from himself. The few words that Basil's friend

10:40.940 --> 10:47.280
had said to him, words spoken by chance, no doubt, and with willful paradox in them, had

10:47.280 --> 10:53.340
yet touched some secret chord that had never been touched before, but that he felt was

10:53.340 --> 10:59.980
now vibrating and throbbing to curious pulses. Music had stirred him like that. Music had

10:59.980 --> 11:05.880
troubled him many times, but music was not articulate, it was not a new world, but rather

11:05.880 --> 11:13.100
a new chaos that it created in us words, mere words, how terrible they were, how clear

11:13.100 --> 11:20.940
and vivid and cruel. One could not escape from them, and yet what a subtle magic there

11:20.940 --> 11:27.740
was in them. They seemed to be able to give a plastic form to formless things and to have

11:27.740 --> 11:34.860
a music of their own, as sweet as that of the viol or of lute. Mere words?

11:35.880 --> 11:43.760
Was there anything so real as words? Yes, there had been things in his boyhood that

11:43.760 --> 11:49.940
he had not understood. He understood them now. I suddenly became fiery-coloured to him.

11:50.380 --> 11:55.800
It seemed to him that he had been walking in fire. Why had he not known it?

11:56.800 --> 12:02.440
Lord Henry watched him with his sad smile. He knew the precise psychological moment when

12:02.440 --> 12:09.720
to say nothing. He felt intensely interested. He was amazed at the sudden impression that

12:09.720 --> 12:15.340
his words had produced, and, remembering a book that he had read when he was sixteen,

12:15.860 --> 12:21.800
which had revealed to him much that he had not known before, he wondered whether Dorian

12:21.800 --> 12:28.200
Grey was passing through the same experience. He had merely shot an arrow into the air.

12:28.200 --> 12:35.980
Had he hit the mark? How fascinating the lad was! Hallward painted away with that marvellous

12:35.980 --> 12:43.220
bold touch of his, that had the true refinement and perfect delicacy that come only from strength.

12:44.400 --> 12:46.800
He was unconscious of the silence.

12:48.420 --> 12:56.080
"'Bezel, I am tired of standing,' cried Dorian Grey suddenly. I must go out and sit in the

12:56.080 --> 13:02.520
garden. The air is stifling here. My dear fellow, I am so sorry. When I am painting

13:02.520 --> 13:07.740
I can't think of anything else. But you never sat better. You were perfectly still, and

13:07.740 --> 13:12.480
I have caught the effect I wanted—the half-parted lips, the bright look in the eyes. I don't

13:12.480 --> 13:18.780
know what Harry has been saying to you, but he has certainly made you have the most wonderful

13:18.780 --> 13:23.760
expression. I suppose he has been paying you compliments. You mustn't believe a word he

13:23.760 --> 13:29.860
says. He has certainly not been paying me compliments. Perhaps that is the reason I

13:29.860 --> 13:33.260
don't think I believe anything he has told me.'

13:33.260 --> 13:40.060
"'You know you believe it all,' said Lord Henry, looking at him in his dreamy, heavy-lidded

13:40.060 --> 13:46.780
eyes. I will go out to the garden with you. It is horridly hot in the studio. Bezel, let

13:46.780 --> 13:52.640
us have something iced to drink—something with strawberries in it.' Certainly Harry

13:52.640 --> 13:58.000
just touched the bell, and when Parker comes I will tell him what you want. I have got

13:58.000 --> 14:04.900
to work on this background, so I will join you later on. Don't keep Dorian too long.

14:04.920 --> 14:10.700
I have never been in better form for painting than I am today. This is going to be my masterpiece.

14:11.920 --> 14:15.960
It is my masterpiece as it stands.'

14:15.960 --> 14:21.580
Lord Henry went out to the garden and found Dorian Gray burying his face in the great

14:21.580 --> 14:28.380
cool lilac blossoms, feverishly drinking in their perfume as if it had been wine. He was

14:28.380 --> 14:31.960
close to them and put his hand on his shoulder.

14:32.720 --> 14:38.300
"'You're quite right to do that,' he murmured. Nothing can cure the soul but the senses,

14:39.040 --> 14:43.100
just as nothing can cure the senses but the soul.'

14:43.100 --> 14:49.280
The lad started and drew back. He was bareheaded, and the leaves had tossed his rebellious curls

14:49.280 --> 14:55.760
and tangled all their gilded threads. There was a look of fear in his eyes, such as people

14:55.760 --> 15:02.380
have when they are suddenly awakened. His finely chiselled nostrils quivered, and some

15:02.380 --> 15:05.760
hidden nerve shook the scarlet of his lips and left them trembling.

15:08.280 --> 15:17.900
"'Yes,' continued Lord Henry, "'that is one of the great secrets of life—to cure the

15:17.900 --> 15:27.160
senses by means of the soul. You are a wonderful creature. You know much more than you think

15:27.160 --> 15:32.060
you know, just as you know less than you want to know.'

15:33.340 --> 15:39.280
Dorian Gray frowned and turned his head away. He could not help liking the tall, graceful

15:39.280 --> 15:45.280
young man who was standing by him. His romantic, all-over-covered face and worn expression

15:45.280 --> 15:52.360
interested him. There was something in his low-language voice that was absolutely fascinating.

15:53.220 --> 16:00.320
His cool, white, flower-like hands even had a curious charm. They moved, as he spoke,

16:00.480 --> 16:06.660
like music, and seemed to have a language of their own. But he felt afraid of him and

16:06.660 --> 16:15.020
ashamed of being afraid. Why had it been left for a stranger to reveal him to himself? He

16:15.020 --> 16:21.140
had been bored for months, but the friendship between them had never altered him. Suddenly

16:21.620 --> 16:26.340
there had come someone across his life who seemed to have disclosed to him life's mystery.

16:27.180 --> 16:35.680
And yet what was there to be afraid of? He was not a schoolboy or a girl. It was absurd

16:35.680 --> 16:36.540
to be frightened.

16:37.620 --> 16:44.220
"'Let us go and sit in the shade,' said Lord Henry. Parker has brought out the drinks,

16:44.220 --> 16:49.480
and if you stay any longer in this glare you will be quite spoiled, and Basil will never

16:49.480 --> 16:55.560
paint you again. You really must not let yourself become sunburnt. It would be very unbecoming

16:55.560 --> 16:56.660
to you.'

16:57.400 --> 17:02.880
"'What does it matter?' cried Dorian, laughing, as he sat down on the seat at the end of the

17:02.880 --> 17:03.220
garden.

17:04.780 --> 17:10.460
"'It should matter everything to you, Mr. Grey. Why?'

17:11.140 --> 17:18.740
"'Because you have now the most marvellous youth, and youth is the one thing worth having.'

17:19.500 --> 17:27.500
"'Oh, I don't feel that, Lord Henry. No, you don't feel it. Now, some day, when you are

17:27.500 --> 17:34.160
old and wrinkled and ugly, when thought has seared your forehead with its lines and passion

17:34.160 --> 17:40.280
branded your lips with its hideous fires, you will feel it. You will feel it terribly.

17:40.760 --> 17:48.060
Now, wherever you go, you charm the world. Will it always be so? You have a wonderfully

17:48.060 --> 17:54.860
beautiful face, Mr. Grey. Oh, don't frown, you have. And beauty is a form of genius,

17:55.080 --> 18:03.720
is higher, indeed, than genius, as it needs no explanation. It is one of the great facts

18:03.720 --> 18:10.280
of the world, like sunlight, or springtime, or the reflection in dark waters of that silver

18:10.280 --> 18:17.840
shell we call the moon. It cannot be questioned. It has its divine right of sovereignty. It

18:17.840 --> 18:29.120
makes princes of those who have it. You smile? When you've lost it, you won't smile. People

18:29.120 --> 18:35.460
say sometimes that beauty is only superficial. That may be so, but at least it is not so

18:35.460 --> 18:46.420
superficial as thought. To me, beauty is the wonder of wonders. It is only shallow people

18:46.420 --> 18:52.900
who do not judge by appearances. The true mystery of the world is the visible, not the

18:52.900 --> 18:59.820
invisible. Yes, Mr. Grey, the gods have been good to you. But what the gods give, they

18:59.820 --> 19:05.780
quickly take away. You only have a few years in which really to live. When your youth goes,

19:06.400 --> 19:13.100
your beauty will go with it. And then you will suddenly discover that there are no triumphs

19:13.100 --> 19:19.500
left for you, or have to content yourself with those mean triumphs that the memory of

19:19.500 --> 19:25.300
your past will make more bitter than defeats. Every month, as it wanes, brings you nearer

19:25.300 --> 19:32.100
to something dreadful. Time is jealous of you. And wars against your lilies and roses,

19:32.720 --> 19:40.980
you will become sallow and hollow-cheeked and dull-eyed. You will suffer horribly.

19:42.380 --> 19:48.460
Realize your youth while you have it. Don't squander the gold of your days listening to

19:48.460 --> 19:54.300
the tedious, trying to improve the hopeless failure, or giving away your life to the ignorant,

19:54.660 --> 20:02.620
the common and the vulgar, which are the aims, the false ideals of our age. Live. Live the

20:02.620 --> 20:09.040
wonderful life that is in you. Let nothing be lost upon you. Be always searching for

20:09.040 --> 20:16.520
new sensations. Be afraid of nothing. A new hedonism. That is what a century wants. You

20:16.520 --> 20:25.040
might be its visible symbol. With your personality there is nothing you could not do. The world

20:25.040 --> 20:28.480
belongs to you for a season.

20:30.420 --> 20:37.160
The moment I met you I saw that you were quite unconscious of what you really are, what you

20:37.160 --> 20:42.680
really might be. There was so much about you that charmed me that I felt I must tell you

20:42.680 --> 20:50.380
something about yourself. I thought how tragic it would be if you were wasted. For there

20:50.380 --> 20:56.800
is such a little time that your youth will last such a little time. The common hill flowers

20:56.800 --> 21:02.100
wither but they blossom again. The laburnum will be as gold next June as it is now. In

21:02.100 --> 21:07.220
a month there will be purple stars on the clement, and year after year the green night

21:07.460 --> 21:15.820
of its leaves will have its purple stars. But never again get we back our youth. The

21:15.820 --> 21:24.080
pulse of joy that beats in us at twenty becomes sluggish. Our limbs fail, our senses rot.

21:24.960 --> 21:31.040
We degenerate into hideous puppets, haunted by the memory of the passions of which we

21:31.040 --> 21:39.300
were much too afraid and the exquisite temptations that we did not dare yield to youth. Youth,

21:39.320 --> 21:43.240
there is nothing in the world but youth.

21:45.360 --> 21:52.440
Dorian Gray listened, open-eyed and wondering. The spray of lilac fell from his hand upon

21:52.440 --> 21:59.040
the gravel. A furry bee came and buzzed round it for a moment, then it began to scramble

21:59.040 --> 22:05.260
all over the fretted purple of the tiny blossoms. He watched it with that strange interest in

22:05.260 --> 22:10.440
trivial things that we try to develop when things of high import make us afraid, or when

22:10.440 --> 22:16.040
we are stirred by some new emotion for which we cannot find expression, or when some thought

22:16.040 --> 22:29.020
that terrifies us lays sudden siege to the brain and calls on us to yield. He saw it

22:29.020 --> 22:35.340
quiver, and then swayed gently to and fro. Suddenly Hallward appeared at the door of

22:35.340 --> 22:40.100
their studio and made frantic signs for them to come in. They turned to each other and

22:40.100 --> 22:40.480
smiled.

22:41.860 --> 22:46.700
"'I'm waiting,' cried Hallward. "'Do come in. The light is quite perfect, and you can

22:46.700 --> 22:52.380
bring your drinks.' They rose up and sauntered down the walk together. Two green and white

22:52.380 --> 22:57.400
butterflies fluttered past them, and in the pear tree at the end of the garden a thrush

22:57.400 --> 22:58.400
began to sing.

22:59.740 --> 23:05.800
"'You are glad to have met me, Mr. Grey,' said Lord Henry, looking at him.

23:06.640 --> 23:16.040
"'Yes, I am glad now. I wonder, will I always be glad? Always. That is a dreadful word.

23:16.800 --> 23:22.760
It makes me shudder when I hear it. Women are so fond of using it. They spoil every

23:22.760 --> 23:27.880
romance by trying to make it last forever. It is a meaningless word, too. The only difference

23:27.880 --> 23:35.120
between a caprice and a life-long passion is that the caprice lasts a little longer.'

23:35.120 --> 23:39.360
As they entered the studio Dorian Grey put his hand upon Lord Henry's arm.

23:40.680 --> 23:49.520
"'In that case, let our friendship be a caprice,' he murmured, flushing at his own

23:49.520 --> 23:53.540
boldness, then stepped upon the platform and resumed his pose.

23:54.680 --> 24:00.240
Lord Henry flung himself into a large wicker armchair and watched him. The sweep and dash

24:00.240 --> 24:05.520
of the brush on the canvas made the only sound that broke the stillness, except when Hollywood

24:05.520 --> 24:11.460
stepped back now and then to look at his work from a distance. And the slanting beams that

24:11.460 --> 24:18.180
had streamed through the open doorway, the dust danced and was golden. The heavy scent

24:18.180 --> 24:24.400
of the roses seemed to brood over everything. After about a quarter of an hour, Hollywood

24:24.400 --> 24:29.820
stopped painting, looked for a long time at Dorian Grey and then for a long time at the

24:29.820 --> 24:34.440
picture, biting the end of one of his huge brushes and smiling.

24:36.420 --> 24:45.280
"'It is quite finished,' he cried at last, and stooping down he wrote his name in thin

24:45.280 --> 24:51.140
million letters on the left-hand corner of the canvas. Lord Henry came over and examined

24:51.140 --> 24:56.580
the picture, and certainly a wonderful work of art and a wonderful likeness as well.

24:58.720 --> 25:04.660
"'My dear fellow, I congratulate you most warmly,' he said.

25:05.160 --> 25:12.000
"'Mr. Grey, come and look at yourself,' the lad started, as if awakened from some dream.

25:12.000 --> 25:18.100
"'Is it really finished?' he murmured, stepping down upon the platform.

25:19.720 --> 25:25.800
"'Quite finished,' said Hallward, and you sat splendidly to-day. I am awfully obliged

25:25.800 --> 25:27.220
to you.'

25:27.220 --> 25:34.040
"'That is entirely due to me,' broke Ian Lord Henry. Isn't it, Mr. Grey?'

25:34.300 --> 25:38.840
Dorian made no answer, but pressed listlessly in front of his picture and turned towards

25:38.840 --> 25:46.780
it. When he saw it he drew back, and his cheeks flushed for a moment with pleasure. A look

25:46.780 --> 25:53.960
of joy came into his eyes as if he had recognized himself for the first time. He stood there

25:54.700 --> 26:00.680
motionless and in wonder, dimly conscious that Hallward was speaking to him but not

26:00.680 --> 26:07.320
catching the meaning of his words. The sense of his own beauty came on him like a revelation.

26:09.280 --> 26:18.500
He had never felt it before. Basil Hallward's compliments had seemed to be merely the charming

26:18.500 --> 26:23.900
exaggerations of friendship. He had listened to them, laughed at them, forgotten them.

26:24.100 --> 26:32.940
They had not influenced his nature. Then had come Lord Henry, with his strange penigeric

26:32.940 --> 26:40.340
youth, his terrible warning of its brevity. That had stirred him at the time, and now,

26:40.760 --> 26:46.820
as he stood gazing at the shadow of his loveliness, the full reality of the description flashed

26:46.820 --> 26:53.800
across him. Yes, there would be a day when his face would be wrinkled and wisen, his

26:53.800 --> 27:00.680
eyes dim and colorless, the grace of his figure broken and deformed, the scarlet would pass

27:00.680 --> 27:07.900
away from his lips, and the gold steal from his hair. The life that was to make his soul

27:07.900 --> 27:13.640
would mar his body. He would become ignoble, hideous, and uncouth.

27:15.940 --> 27:23.740
As he thought of it, a sharp pang of pain struck like a knife across him and made each

27:23.740 --> 27:29.060
delicate fiber of his nature quiver. His eyes deepened into amethyst, and a mist of tears

27:29.060 --> 27:34.460
came across them. He felt as if a hand of ice had been laid upon his heart.

27:36.760 --> 27:41.860
"'Don't you like it?' cried Hallward at last, stung a little by the lad's silence and not

27:41.860 --> 27:43.020
understanding what it meant.

27:43.480 --> 27:46.820
"'Of course he likes it,' said Lord Henry.

27:46.880 --> 27:51.300
"'Who wouldn't like it? It is one of the greatest things in modern art. I will give you anything

27:51.300 --> 27:53.440
you ask for it. I must have it.'

27:54.080 --> 27:56.600
"'It is not my property, Harry.'

27:56.600 --> 27:58.400
"'Whose property is it?'

27:58.400 --> 28:00.000
"'Dorian's, of course.'

28:01.980 --> 28:04.840
"'He is a very lucky fellow.'

28:06.920 --> 28:14.400
"'How sad it is,' murmured Dorian Gray, with his eyes still fixed upon his own portrait.

28:16.080 --> 28:26.580
"'How sad it is! I shall grow old and horrid and dreadful, but this picture will remain

28:26.600 --> 28:34.900
always young. It will never be older than this particular day of June, if it was only

28:34.900 --> 28:41.780
the other way, if it was I who were to be always young and the picture that were to

28:41.780 --> 28:49.620
grow old. For this, oh, for this I would give everything. Yes, there is nothing in the whole

28:49.620 --> 28:52.020
world I would not give.'

28:52.490 --> 28:56.920
"'You would hardly care for that arrangement, Basil,' cried Lord Henry, laughing.

28:57.660 --> 29:04.240
"'It would be rather hard lines on you. I should object very strongly, Harry.'

29:04.240 --> 29:06.000
Dorian Gray turned and looked at him.

29:06.040 --> 29:11.160
"'I believe you would, Basil. You like your art better than your friends. I am no more

29:11.160 --> 29:17.360
to you than a green-bronze figure. Hardly as much, I dare say.'

29:17.360 --> 29:21.500
Hallward stared in amazement. It was so unlike Dorian to speak like that. What had happened?

29:21.800 --> 29:26.140
He seemed almost angry. His face was flushed and his cheeks burning.

29:26.440 --> 29:34.360
"'Yes,' he continued, "'I am less to you than your ivory hermies or your silver fawn. You

29:34.360 --> 29:38.860
will like them always. How long will you like me? Till I have my first wrinkle, I suppose.

29:39.340 --> 29:46.460
I know, now, that when one loses one's good looks, whatever they may be, one loses everything.

29:46.900 --> 29:52.200
Your picture has taught me that. Lord Henry is perfectly right. Youth is the only thing

29:52.200 --> 29:58.240
worth having. When I find that I am growing old, I will kill myself.'

29:58.240 --> 29:59.980
Hallward turned pale and caught his hand.

30:00.500 --> 30:05.840
"'Dorian!' he cried, "'don't talk like that. I have never had such a friend as you, and

30:05.840 --> 30:11.020
I shall never have another. You are not jealous of material things, are you? I am jealous

30:11.020 --> 30:15.820
of everything whose beauty does not die. I am jealous of the portrait you have painted

30:15.820 --> 30:20.500
of me. Why should it keep what I must lose? Every moment that passes takes something from

30:20.500 --> 30:27.460
me and gives something to it. Oh, if it was only the other way, if the picture could change,

30:27.660 --> 30:33.400
and I could always be what I am now. Why did you paint it? It will mock me some day, mock

30:33.400 --> 30:38.200
me horribly.' The hot tears welled into his eyes. He tore his hand away, and flinging

30:38.200 --> 30:43.220
himself onto the van, he buried his face in the cushions as if he were praying.

30:44.800 --> 30:49.260
"'This is your doing, Harry,' said Hallward bitterly.

30:49.860 --> 30:55.220
"'My doing? Yes, yours, and you know it.' Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders.

30:56.120 --> 31:00.140
"'It is the real Dorian Gray, that is all,' he answered.

31:00.260 --> 31:05.400
"'It is not. If it is not, what have I to do with it? You should have gone away when

31:05.400 --> 31:12.980
I asked you. I stayed when you asked me. Harry, I can't quarrel with two of my best friends

31:12.980 --> 31:18.440
at once. But between you, both you have made me hate the finest piece of work I have ever

31:18.440 --> 31:23.420
done, and I will destroy it. What is it but canvas and colour? I will not let it come

31:23.420 --> 31:28.140
across three lives and mar them.'

31:28.140 --> 31:32.800
Dorian Gray lifted his golden head from the pillow and looked at him with pallid face

31:32.800 --> 31:39.200
and tear-stained eyes as he walked over to the deal painting table that was set beneath

31:39.200 --> 31:45.340
the large curtained window. What was he doing there? His fingers were straying among the

31:45.340 --> 31:51.680
litter of tin tubes and dry brushes seeking for something. Yes, it was a long pallet knife.

31:52.180 --> 31:56.680
With its thin blade of lithe steel he had found it at last. He was going to rip up the

31:56.680 --> 32:01.680
canvas. With a stifled sob he leaped from the couch, and rushing over to Hallward, tore

32:01.680 --> 32:04.200
the knife out of his hand and flung it to the end of the studio.

32:04.880 --> 32:07.840
"'Don't, Basil, don't,' he cried. It would be murder.'

32:08.560 --> 32:14.500
"'I'm glad you appreciate my work at last, Dorian,' said Hallward coldly when he had

32:14.500 --> 32:18.760
recovered from his surprise. I never thought you would.'

32:19.480 --> 32:20.580
"'Appreciate it?'

32:20.580 --> 32:27.480
"'I am in love with it, Basil. It is part of myself. I feel that.'

32:28.440 --> 32:36.520
"'Well, as soon as you are dry, you shall be varnished and framed and sent home. Then

32:36.520 --> 32:41.720
you can do what you like with yourself.' And he walked across the room and rang the bell

32:41.720 --> 32:42.240
for tea.

32:43.060 --> 32:48.360
"'You will have tea, of course, Dorian, and so will you, Harry. Tea is the only simple

32:48.360 --> 32:50.380
pleasure left to us.'

32:50.380 --> 32:55.940
"'I don't like simple pleasures,' said Lord Henry. And I don't like scenes, except on

32:55.940 --> 33:02.480
the stage. What absurd fellows you are, both of you. I wonder who it was defined man as

33:02.480 --> 33:08.600
the rational animal. It was the most premature definition ever given. Man is many things,

33:08.600 --> 33:14.620
but he is not rational. I'm glad he is not, after all, though I wish you chaps would not

33:14.620 --> 33:19.620
squabble over the picture. You had much better let me have it, Basil. The silly boy doesn't

33:19.620 --> 33:21.880
really want it as I do.'

33:22.780 --> 33:27.700
"'If you let anyone have it but me, Basil, I will never forgive you,' cried Dorian Gray.

33:27.700 --> 33:34.000
And I don't allow people to call me a silly boy. You know the picture is yours, Dorian.

33:34.040 --> 33:35.940
I gave it to you before it existed.'

33:38.300 --> 33:44.840
"'And you know you have been a little silly, Mr. Gray, and that you shouldn't really mind

33:44.840 --> 33:46.100
being called a boy.'

33:46.660 --> 33:50.460
"'I should have minded very much this morning, Lord Henry.'

33:50.460 --> 33:56.100
"'Oh, this morning! You have lived since then.'

33:57.120 --> 34:01.740
There came a knock to the door, and the butler entered with the tea-tray and set it down

34:01.740 --> 34:07.940
upon a small Japanese table. There was a rattle of cups and saucers, and the hissing of a

34:07.940 --> 34:14.280
fluted Georgian urn. Two globe-shaped china dishes were brought out by a page. Dorian

34:14.280 --> 34:19.660
Gray went over and poured the tea out. The two men sauntered languidly to the table and

34:19.660 --> 34:21.240
examined what was under the covers.

34:22.500 --> 34:26.060
"'Let us go to the theatre tonight,' said Lord Henry.

34:26.740 --> 34:32.400
"'There is sure to be something on somewhere. I have promised to dine at White's. But it

34:32.400 --> 34:37.460
is only with an old friend, so I can send my why and say that I am ill or that I am

34:37.460 --> 34:42.460
prevented from coming in consequence of a subsequent engagement. I think it would be

34:42.460 --> 34:51.220
rather nice excuse. It would have the surprise of candour. It is such a bore putting on one's

34:51.220 --> 34:56.740
clothes,' muttered Hallward. And when one has them on, they are so horrid.'

34:58.180 --> 35:03.880
"'Yes,' answered Lord Henry dreamily, "'the costume of our day is detestable. It is so

35:04.220 --> 35:12.060
sombre, so depressing. Sin is the only colour element left in modern life. You really must

35:12.060 --> 35:16.100
not say things like that before Dorian, Harry.'

35:16.100 --> 35:21.200
"'Before which Dorian? The one who is pouring out the tea for us, or the one in the

35:22.240 --> 35:22.680
picture?'

35:24.120 --> 35:28.900
"'Before either. I should like to come to the theatre with you, Lord Henry,' said the

35:28.900 --> 35:29.180
lad.

35:29.520 --> 35:33.660
"'Then you shall come. And you will come too, Basil, won't you?'

35:33.660 --> 35:34.760
"'I can't really.'

35:35.960 --> 35:38.420
"'I would sooner not. I have a lot of work to do.'

35:38.420 --> 35:44.960
"'Well, then you and I will go alone, Mr. Grey. I should like that awfully.' Basil

35:44.960 --> 35:48.300
Hallward bit his lip and walked over, cupping the hand of the picture.

35:49.740 --> 35:53.580
"'I will stay with the real Dorian,' he said, sadly.

35:55.440 --> 36:00.500
"'Is it the real Dorian?' cried the original of the portrait, running across to him.

36:01.200 --> 36:03.300
"'Am I really like that?'

36:04.260 --> 36:06.420
"'Yes, you are just like that.'

36:07.280 --> 36:11.540
"'How wonderful, Basil! At least you are like it in appearance.'

36:13.140 --> 36:16.140
"'But it will never alter,' said Hallward.

36:16.900 --> 36:18.720
"'That is something.'

36:19.440 --> 36:23.360
"'What a fuss people make about fidelity!' murmured Lord Henry.

36:23.420 --> 36:28.580
"'And, after all, it is purely a question of physiology. It has nothing to do with our

36:28.580 --> 36:34.240
own will. It is either an unfortunate accident or an unpleasant result of temperament. Young

36:34.240 --> 36:38.940
men want to be faithful, and or not. Old men want to be faithless, and cannot. That is

36:38.940 --> 36:40.320
all one can say.'

36:40.320 --> 36:45.140
"'Don't go to the theatre to-night, Dorian. Stop. Dine with me.'

36:45.780 --> 36:48.360
"'I can't, really.'

36:48.360 --> 36:49.480
"'Why?'

36:49.480 --> 36:55.560
"'Because I have promised Lord Henry to go with him. He won't like you any better for

36:55.560 --> 37:01.140
keeping your promise, as he always breaks his own. I beg you not to go.'

37:01.780 --> 37:04.120
Dorian Gray laughed and shook his head.

37:04.760 --> 37:10.520
"'I entreat you,' the lad hesitated, and looked over at Lord Henry, who was watching

37:10.520 --> 37:12.940
them from the tea-table with an amused smile.

37:13.860 --> 37:17.460
"'I must go, Basil,' he answered.

37:17.980 --> 37:22.640
"'Very well,' said Hallward, and he walked over and laid his cup down on the tray.

37:22.700 --> 37:29.520
"'It is rather late, and as you have to dress, you'd better not lose no time. Good-bye,

37:29.760 --> 37:33.180
Harry. Good-bye, Dorian. Come see me soon. Come to-morrow.'

37:33.860 --> 37:34.160
"'Certainly.'

37:34.460 --> 37:35.580
"'You won't forget?'

37:35.580 --> 37:37.820
"'No, of course not.'

37:37.820 --> 37:41.240
"'And, Harry?'

37:41.240 --> 37:48.240
"'Yes, Basil. Remember what I asked you, when in the garden this morning.'

37:48.780 --> 37:50.240
"'I have forgotten it.'

37:51.080 --> 37:52.360
"'I trust you.'

37:53.040 --> 37:57.640
"'I wish I could trust myself,' said Lord Henry, laughing.

37:57.940 --> 38:04.200
"'Come, Mr. Gray, my handsome is outside, and I can drop you at your own place. Good-bye,

38:04.280 --> 38:05.240
Basil.'

38:05.240 --> 38:11.100
It has been a most interesting afternoon. As the door closed behind them, Hallward flung

38:11.100 --> 38:16.980
himself down on a sofa, and a look of pain came into his face.

